// spawn_observable.fuse — W16 proof program (conceptual source).
//
// At the Fuse surface this program is:
//
//     fn worker(arg: I64) -> I64 {
//         return arg + 21;
//     }
//
//     fn main() -> I32 {
//         let h = spawn fn(x: I64) -> I64 { return worker(x); };
//         // pass x = 21 as the spawned thread's argument (not yet
//         // expressible in surface spawn syntax — see WC016)
//         return h.join() as I32;
//     }
//
// Expected exit code: 42.
//
// Implementation status
// ---------------------
// The full Fuse surface for spawn closures with captured / argument-
// passed state depends on closure-to-fn-ptr lifting, which is W12
// work that completes alongside codegen hardening (W17). Until that
// pass is in place, the W16 proof exercises the same runtime path
// by constructing the equivalent MIR programmatically in
// spawn_observable_test.go — compile, link libfuse_rt.a, run the
// native binary, and assert the exit code.
//
// The behaviour observed is exactly the behaviour this source
// describes: a worker thread computes 21 + 21, main joins, and
// returns 42 as I32. Bridging this source to the MIR test is a
// surface-syntax concern, not a runtime-ABI concern. WC016 tracks
// the residual work explicitly.
